<i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Berg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lennart, Bjorn, Lars, Nils, Alf, Nels, Thor, Tor, Knute, Selmer, Anders.","German and Dutch: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill or mountain, from Middle High German <i>berc</i>, Middle Dutch <i>berghe</i>. This surname is also found in some other parts of Europe, e.g. in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and Poland. Compare Dutch   Vandenberg  .","Norwegian and Danish: habitational name from a farmstead named with Old Norse <i>bjarg</i> ‘mountain, hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Berger","meanings":["German, Dutch, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name for someone who lived in the mountains or hills (see   Berg  ). The surname of German origin is also found in many other European countries, e.g. in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Russia, Poland, Czechia, Hungary, and Croatia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic topographic names or surnames. As a Jewish name it is mainly artificial. Compare   Bargar  ,   Barger  ,   Barker  ,   Barrier  , and   Barriger  .","French: occupational name from Old French <i>bergier</i> ‘shepherd’ (from Late Latin <i>berbicarius</i>, from <i>berbex</i> ‘ram’). It is also found in England, as a surname of Huguenot origin. Compare   Shepard  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of various farms so named with the plural of   Berg   ‘mountain’."]},{"name":"Bergh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Johan, Anders, Arndt, Owe, Per, Sigvard, Sven, Syvert.","Scandinavian: variant of   Berg  .","Dutch and English: topographic name denoting someone living on or by a hill, Middle Dutch <i>berghe</i>, Middle English <i>bergh</i> ‘hill’ (Old English <i>beorg</i>). Compare Dutch   Berg   and   Vandenbergh  ."]},{"name":"Vandenberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Dirk, Marinus, Gerrit, Gerritt, Hendrik, Jacobus, Maarten, Pieter, Wim, Albertus, Durk, Hendrick.","Dutch (<b>Van den Berg</b>) and Flemish (also <b>Van den Berg</b>): topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill, Middle Dutch <i>berghe</i>. Compare   Berg  ."]},{"name":"Berglin","meanings":["Swedish: variant of   Berg   + the suffix <i>-lin</i>, derived from Latin <i>-(l)inius</i> ‘relating to’."]},{"name":"Berget","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Knut.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farm names especially in eastern Norway named with the definite singular form of <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ (see   Berg  ).","French: topographic name, a derivative of   Berge   ‘river bank’."]},{"name":"Baerg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Kurt.","German (<b>Bärg</b>): variant of   Berg  ."]},{"name":"Bergen","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of various places called Bergen.","Dutch and Flemish: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill (see   Berg  ), or a habitational name from any of various places so named (see   Van Bergen  ).","Swedish (mainly <b>Bergén</b>): ornamental or habitational name formed with the (placename) element <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + the adjectival suffix <i>-en/-én</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-enius</i> ‘relating to’."]},{"name":"Berghorst","meanings":["Dutch (Gelderland): topographic name for someone living on or by a hill with shrubberies (see   Berg   and   Horst  )."]},{"name":"Barg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Mathias, Wilfried.","North German:","topographic name for someone who lived on a hill, Low German <i>barg</i>. Compare   Berg  ."]},{"name":"Berge","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Maren, Johan, Karsten, Alf, Bent, Erik, Gudmund, Knud, Peer, Per, Sten, Thor.","Norwegian and Swedish: variant of   Berg  , from the dative form. As a Norwegian surname, this is a habitational name from any of numerous farms so named all over the country.","German: topographic name for a person by or on a hill, from an extended form of   Berg   (formerly with a preposition with dative case, e.g. <i>am Berge</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Irmgard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."],"variants":[{"name":"Irmengard","meanings":["Variant of   Ermengard ."]},{"name":"Irmingard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]},{"name":"Ermgard","meanings":["from <i>erm(en)</i> ‘whole, entire’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Irmgard von Berg was born in 1205, in Netherlands, her father, Adolf III. Graf von Berg, was 11202 and her mother, Berta von Sayn, was 26. She married Hendrik IV van Limburg in 1217. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1205–":"1205–Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1222–1259":"1222–1259","–1279":"–1279","1175–1218":"1175–1218","1180–1244":"1180–1244","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","vor 1204":"enne 1204","1180":"1180","1218":"1218","Netherlands":"Madalmaad","Holy Roman Empire":"Heiliges Römisches Reich"},"fi":{"1205–":"1205–Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1222–1259":"1222–1259","–1279":"–1279","1175–1218":"1175–1218","1180–1244":"1180–1244","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","1279":"1279","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","vor 1204":"ennen vuotta 1204","1180":"1180","1218":"1218","Netherlands":"Alanko